 of history from the fictions constructed in works of art? How do art historians employ or resist devices of fiction, and what are the effects of those choices on the reader? In styles by turns witty, elliptical, and plain-speaking, the essays in Fictions of Art History are fascinating and provocative critical interventions in art history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aArt in literaturevCongresses. 0aArtxHistoriographyvCongresses. 0aFictionxHistory and criticismvCongresses. 7aART / Criticism.2bisacsh1 aBarolsky, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrow, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHatt, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKury, Gloria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLedbury, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLieberman, Ralph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoh, Maria H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNemerov, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScott, Joanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSwensen, Cole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTorgovnick, Marianna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVout, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWarner, Marina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030019192940uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300192148?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/